  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sets international standards for preventing money laundering\n- Recommends global policies and practices\n- 39 member jurisdictions collaborate to combat financial crimes\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n- Provide frameworks for international cooperation\n\n3. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- Establishes banking supervision standards\n- Provides recommendations for identifying and preventing money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Regulations\n- Helps member countries develop anti-money laundering frameworks\n- Provides technical assistance and guidance\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish continent-wide standards for preventing financial crimes\n- Regularly updated to address emerging risks\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal control mechanisms\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
